      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for your query:\n\n## \"Progress Measures for Grokking via Mechanistic Interpretability\"\n\n**Authors:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Neel Nanda, Lawrence Chan, Tom Lieberum, Jess Smith, Jacob Steinhardt"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Venue:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Published at ICLR 2023 as an in-person poster presentation / top 25% paper"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": ", and also presented as an [oral](https://iclr.cc/virtual/2023/oral/12572).\n\n**ArXiv:** [2301.05217](https://arxiv.org/abs/2301.05217), first submitted January 12, 2023.\n\n### Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Neural networks often exhibit emergent behavior, where qualitatively new capabilities arise from scaling up parameters, training data, or training steps. One approach to understanding emergence is to find continuous progress measures that underlie the seemingly discontinuous qualitative changes."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The authors argue that progress measures can be found via mechanistic interpretability: reverse-engineering learned behaviors into their individual components. As a case study, they investigate the recently-discovered phenomenon of \"grokking\" exhibited by small transformers trained on modular addition tasks."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Key Findings\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "They fully reverse engineer the algorithm learned by these networks, which uses discrete Fourier transforms and trigonometric identities to convert addition to rotation about a circle."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Based on this understanding, they define progress measures that allow studying the dynamics of training and split training into three continuous phases: memorization, circuit formation, and cleanup."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Their results show that grokking, rather than being a sudden shift, arises from the gradual amplification of structured mechanisms encoded in the weights, followed by the later removal of memorizing components."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The authors see their result as demonstrating both that it is possible to fully reverse engineer trained networks, and that doing so can be invaluable to understanding their training dynamics."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Links\n- **ArXiv:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2301.05217\n- **OpenReview:** https://openreview.net/forum?id=9XFSbDPmdW\n- **ICLR 2023 page:** https://iclr.cc/virtual/2023/poster/11385\n- **Semantic Scholar:** https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/f680d47a51a0e470fcb228bf0110c026535ead1b"
      }
